[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.1 Aviation, in contrast to most other forms of public transport,
[normal] 
[normal]pays its own way
[normal] and i
[normal]n terms of infrastructure investment – both by airports and airlines – the industry receiv
[normal]es little or no public subsidy.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2 
[normal]We we
[normal]lcome the government’s announcement establishing the 
[normal]Regional Air Connectivity fund
[normal],
[normal] but the £10million being set aside to support 
[normal]to ensure that regions outside the Hig
[normal]h Speed Rail 2 network will
[normal] benefit from stronger transport links
[normal] is small beer compare
[normal]d to the public
[normal] subsidy given to rail and bus.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3 We support the government’s 
[normal]commitment to re-balancing the economy away from the south-east and believe that greater support for regional aviation 
[normal]can be an important tool in that rebalancing.
[normal] 
[normal]Flybe has commissioned a study from Oxford Economics to explore the impact of regional aviation and connectivity on GDP, the relationship between regional aviation and growth, inward investment, business supply-chains, tourism and employment. The report wi
[normal]ll be 
[normal]ready in the autumn and we trust 
[normal]will help 
[normal]inform the debate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4 
[normal]A measure of how the regions – not only ‘isolated’ communities – have lost connectivity over the years is best exemplified by the statistics relating to access to London Heathrow airport. 
[normal]Only six UK cities (Aberdeen, Belfast, Edinburgh, Glasgow, Mancheste
[normal]r and Newcastle) 
[normal]currently 
[normal]have access to Heathrow, compared to some 20 airports
[normal] (in
[normal]cluding the likes of Inverness, Newquay, Plymouth and Humberside)
[normal] 
[normal]that 
[normal]had such access in 1990
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5 
[normal]We fear that 
[normal]within two years London Gatwick will have gone the same w
[normal]ay
[normal], given 
[normal]the CAA’s failure to uphold Flybe’s complaint against London Gatwick’s owners following price rises of 102% over a five year period. Despite the plainly unreasonable and discriminatory nature of such rises, the CAA concluded that Gatwick’s object
[normal]ive in restructuring its charges to ‘increase the efficient use of its s
[normal]ingle runway’ was justifiable. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.6 The challenges that isolated communities face as a result are even greater, given the need for two and sometimes three flights to reach an internat
[normal]ional destination. Airlines like ourselves try to assist our passengers wherever possible by operating direct routes to 
[normal]international hubs, such as Exeter to Paris CDG or Inverness to Amsterdam. This enables them to access global airports and negates the n
[normal]eed for hours spent on the road driving to say London Heathrow or Birmingham. 
[normal]More direct routes could be introduced were the funding available.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.7 Another alternative Flybe has developed is the Manchester hub.
[normal] Intro
[normal]duced in March 2012, we
[normal] created a regi
[normal]onal network hub by optimising scheduling options through Manchester airport, meaning that Flybe passengers instantly benefitted from an additional 86 regional point-to-point connections.
[normal] 
[normal]By working with Manchester Airport to streamline connectivity and re
[normal]duce minimum connecting times to as little as 35 minutes, Flybe significantly added to the choice of our domestic flights, giving passengers an affordable choice of multiple day returns throughout the UK. While the hub can never be, and does not seek to be
[normal], a rival to Heathrow, it has created a long-haul alternative to for the UK’s regional communities, allowing them to access flight connections to the rest of the world offered from Manchester Airport.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.1 
[normal]Air Passenger Duty is a barrier to economic growth. It is well documented that the UK has the highest aviation tax in the world – a seriously short-sighted policy for an island nation. Indeed, the government themselves have explicitly acknowledged that APD
[normal] constrains demand, evidenced by their decision 
[normal]in 2011 
[normal]to approve a reduction in Continental’s APD from Belfast International to Newark in order to retain the service.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2 
[normal]As can be seen from the table below, the numbers of UK domestic air 
[normal]passengers has
[normal] fallen by more than a fifth
[normal] since 2007-08. While this drop has been in part the product of the recession and continuing economic challenges, the fact that APD for a domestic flight was £5 per passenger per flight in 2007-08 and is now £13 per passenger pe
[normal]r flight has undoubtedly had an impact.
